Defender for servers plan  

This plan includes the integrated license for Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, security baselines and OS level assessments, vulnerability assessment scanning, adaptive application controls (AAC), file integrity monitoring (FIM), 

- Microsoft Defender for Servers includes an automatic, native integration with Microsoft Defender for Endpoint 
    
- With this integration enabled, you have access to the vulnerability findings from Microsoft threat and vulnerability management. 
    
- Defender for Servers Plan 1: you can enable / disable the plan at the resource level. 
    
- Defender for Servers Plan 2: you can only disable the plan at the resource level. For example, it’s possible to enable the plan at the subscription level and disable specific resources, however it’s not possible to enable the plan only for specific resources 
    

Microsoft Defender for Cloud's Defender for Servers plans contains components that monitor your environments to provide extended coverage on your servers. Each of these components can be enabled, disabled or configured to your meet your specific requirements 

Data Collection in Defender for Cloud  

Defender for Cloud collects data from your Azure virtual machines (VMs), Virtual Machine Scale Sets, IaaS containers, and non-Azure (including on-premises) machines to monitor for security vulnerabilities and threats. Some Defender plans require monitoring components to collect data from your workloads. 

Data collection is required to provide visibility into missing updates, misconfigured OS security settings, endpoint protection status, and health and threat protection 

Visibility into the security of your workloads depends on the data that the monitoring components collect. The components ensure security coverage for all supported resources. 

To save you the process of manually installing the extensions, Defender for Cloud reduces management overhead by installing all required extensions on existing and new machines. Defender for Cloud assigns the appropriate Deploy if not exists policy to the workloads in the subscription. This policy type ensures the extension is provisioned on all existing and future resources of that type. 

When Defender for Cloud is enabled on the VM, it will automatically install the Log Analytics agent extension. 

Log Analytics agent supports multi-homing, which means it can report data to multiple workspaces simultaneously. This capability ensures flexibility in data collection and analysis, enabling organizations to centralize security monitoring while maintaining existing configurations.

Adaptive Application Control in Defender for Servers Plan2 

Helps us to deal with malicious or unauthorized softwares by allowing only specific applications to run on machines 

MDC requires atleast two weeks of data to give unique recommendations per group of machines 

Creates allow list rules for each group and presents the rule in the form of recommendation, once the recommendation is resolved, DFC configures it by leveraging app locker capabilities 

- controls enhance your security with this data-driven, intelligent automated solution that defines allowlists of known-safe applications for your machines 
    
- Microsoft Defender for Cloud uses machine learning to analyze the applications running on your machines and create a list of the known-safe software 
    
- Adaptive application controls are intended to provide security alerts if any application runs other than the ones you define as safe. 
    

- Configured - Groups of machines that already have a defined allowlist of applications. For each group, the configured tab shows: 
    
- the number of machines in the group 
    
- recent alerts 
    
- Recommended - Groups of machines that consistently run the same applications, and don't have an allowlist configured. We recommend that you enable adaptive application controls for these groups. 
    

If you see a group name with the prefix REVIEWGROUP, it contains machines with a partially consistent list of applications. Microsoft Defender for Cloud can't see a pattern but recommends reviewing this group to see whether you can manually define some adaptive application controls rules as described in [Edit a group's adaptive application controls rule](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/defender-for-cloud/enable-adaptive-application-controls#edit-a-groups-adaptive-application-controls-rule). 

Move a machine from one group to another 

When you move a machine from one group to another, the application control policy applied to it changes to the settings of the group that you moved it to. You can also move a machine from a configured group to a non-configured group, which removes any application control rules that were applied to the machine

Change in OS files, Windows registries files, application software, and Linux system files 

Attackers may attempt to modify or delete critical operating system files to disrupt system functionality or gain unauthorized access. 

Replacing system executables like cmd.exe or lsass.exe with malicious versions can allow attackers to execute arbitrary commands or escalate privileges. 

Rootkits are malicious software designed to conceal their presence and activities on the system. They often target operating system files to hide their presence and evade detection by security tools. 

Attackers may manipulate registry values to cause system instability or manipulate user settings.  

Shell Scripts: Attackers may modify or inject malicious code into shell scripts used for system administration or automation tasks. 

Monitoring the system32 directory for changes is essential because any unauthorized modification to these files can severely impact system stability and security. Detecting such changes promptly can help prevent further exploitation and ensure the integrity of the operating system. 

An attacker injects malicious registry keys into the Windows registry to achieve persistence and execute malicious code during system startup. 

 affect system stability, security, and performance 

 File Monitoring 

File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) examines operating system files, Windows registries, application software, and Linux system files for changes that might indicate an attack. 

FIM (file integrity monitoring) uses the Azure Change Tracking solution to track and identify changes in your environment. When FIM is enabled, you have a Change Tracking resource of type Solution. If you remove the Change Tracking resource, you'll also disable the File Integrity Monitoring feature in Defender for Cloud. 

Change Tracking 

This feature tracks changes in virtual machines hosted in Azure, on-premises, and other cloud environments to help you pinpoint operational and environmental issues with software managed by the Distribution Package Manager. Items that are tracked by Change Tracking and Inventory include: 

- Windows software 
    
- Linux software (packages) 
    
- Windows and Linux files 
    
- Windows registry keys 
    
- Windows services 
    
- Linux daemons 
    

Change Tracking and Inventory makes use of [Microsoft Defender for Cloud File Integrity Monitoring (FIM)](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/security-center/security-center-file-integrity-monitoring) to examine operating system and application files, and Windows Registry. While FIM monitors those entities, Change Tracking and Inventory natively tracks: 

- Software changes 
    
- Windows services 
    
- Linux daemons 
    

Change Tracking and Inventory forwards data to Azure Monitor Logs, and this collected data is stored in a Log Analytics workspace. The File Integrity Monitoring (FIM) feature is available only when Microsoft Defender for servers is enabled 

Machines linked to log analytics workspace use log analytics agent to collect data about changes to installed software, Windows services, Windows registry and files, and Linux daemons on monitored servers. 

Change Tracking inventory>> forwards data to Azure monitor Logs>> data stored in log analytics workspace 

Azure Monitor Logs applies logic to the received data, records it, and makes it available for analysis. 

Limitation in Change Inventory 

.exe files stored on Windows 

Refer for limitations       [https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/automation/change-tracking/overview?tabs=python-2](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/automation/change-tracking/overview?tabs=python-2)

Adaptive Network Hardening 

Adaptive network hardening is an agentless feature of Microsoft Defender for Cloud - nothing needs to be installed on your machines to benefit from this network hardening tool. 

Required Roles and permissions: Write permissions on the machine’s NSGs  

- When implementing network security groups (NSGs) to filter traffic to and from resources, it's crucial to align the NSG rules with the actual traffic patterns to maximize security effectiveness. However, there may be scenarios where the defined NSG rules are broader than the actual traffic flow, leaving potential security gaps. In such cases, hardening the NSG rules based on observed traffic patterns can further improve the security posture 
    
    - Example 
        
    
    When implementing network security groups (NSGs) to filter traffic to and from resources, it's crucial to align the NSG rules with the actual traffic patterns to maximize security effectiveness. However, there may be scenarios where the defined NSG rules are broader than the actual traffic flow, leaving potential security gaps. In such cases, hardening the NSG rules based on observed traffic patterns can further improve the security posture. 
    
    Here's a real-time example to illustrate this concept: 
    
    Scenario: Imagine a company hosts a web application on Azure, consisting of a web server (VM) and a database server (VM). The NSG associated with these VMs has broad rules allowing HTTP (port 80) and HTTPS (port 443) traffic from any source to reach the web server, as well as allowing SQL traffic (port 1433) from any source to reach the database server. 
    
    Observation: Upon monitoring the actual traffic patterns over time, it is observed that: 
    
    1. The web server primarily receives HTTP traffic (port 80) from a specific set of IP addresses corresponding to legitimate users and bots. 
        
    2. The database server only receives SQL traffic (port 1433) from the web server's IP address for database queries. 
        
    
    Action: Based on the observed traffic patterns, the NSG rules can be hardened to better align with the actual traffic flow, thereby improving the security posture. The following adjustments can be made: 
    
    3. Web Server NSG: 
        
        - Update the NSG rule to allow inbound HTTP traffic (port 80) only from the specific set of IP addresses corresponding to legitimate users and bots. 
            
        - Remove the broader rule allowing HTTP traffic from any source. 
            
    4. Database Server NSG: 
        
        - Update the NSG rule to allow inbound SQL traffic (port 1433) only from the web server's IP address. 
            
        - Remove the broader rule allowing SQL traffic from any source 
            
    
- Adaptive network hardening provides recommendations to further harden the NSG rules. It uses a machine learning algorithm that factors in actual traffic, known trusted configuration, threat intelligence, and other indicators of compromise, and then provides recommendations to allow traffic only from specific IP/port tuples. 
    
- Recommendations 
    
    - Unscanned resources: VMs that the adaptive network hardening algorithm cannot be run on because of one of the following reasons: 
        
        - VMs are Classic VMs: Only Azure Resource Manager VMs are supported. 
            
        - Not enough data is available: In order to generate accurate traffic hardening recommendations, Defender for Cloud requires at least 30 days of traffic data. 
            
        - VM is not protected by Microsoft Defender for Servers: Only VMs protected with [Microsoft Defender for Servers](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/defender-for-cloud/defender-for-servers-introduction) are eligible for this feature 
            
    - select a VM to view its alerts and the recommended hardening rules to apply. 
        
        - The Rules tab lists the rules that adaptive network hardening recommends you add 
            
        - The Alerts tab lists the alerts that were generated due to traffic, flowing to the resource, which is not within the IP range allowed in the recommended rules. 
            

 edit the rules: 

- [Modify a rule](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/defender-for-cloud/adaptive-network-hardening#modify-rule) 
    
- [Delete a rule](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/defender-for-cloud/adaptive-network-hardening#delete-rule) 
    
- [Add a rule](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/defender-for-cloud/adaptive-network-hardening#add-rule) 
    

Note: If the allowed source IP ranges shows as 'None', it means that recommended rule is a deny rule, otherwise, it is an allow rule. 

Modify a Rule:  

might want to modify the parameters of a rule that has been recommended 

- Cannot change allow rules to become deny rules 
    
- Can modify parameters of allow rules only 
    
- A Deny all traffic rule is the only type of "deny" rule that would be listed here, and it cannot be modified 
    

Add a Rule:  

- Only allow rules can be added,  
    

 If you want to add "deny" rules, you can do so directly on the NSG.  

Delete a Rule:  

you might determine that applying a suggested rule could block legitimate traffic. 

Defender for App Service 

DFC is integrated with App Service eliminating the need for deployment and onboarding - the integration is transparent. 

Microsoft Defender for App Service uses the scale of the cloud to identify attacks targeting applications running over App Service. Attackers probe web applications to find and exploit weaknesses 

Before being routed to specific environments, requests to applications running in Azure go through several gateways, where they're inspected and logged.  

- Defender for App Service continuously monitors various aspects of your App Service resources to detect potential threats. 
    
- It monitors the VM instance hosting your App Service, including its management interface, to identify any suspicious activities or unauthorized access attempts. 
    
- It also analyses the requests and responses sent to and from your App Service apps, looking for signs of malicious behaviour or abnormal patterns. 
    
- Additionally, it monitors the underlying sandboxes and VMs associated with your App Service for any indicators of compromise. 
    
- It leverages internal logs of your App Service provided by Azure, which offers visibility into the operation of your apps and infrastructure within the Azure cloud environment 
    

Microsoft Defender for App Service is like a security guard for your web applications hosted on Azure. It has the ability to identify attack methods that target multiple applications simultaneously, which can be challenging to detect from just one location. 

For example, if there's an attack happening where a small group of computers are trying to access similar parts of your web applications from different locations, it might be hard to spot this if you're only looking at the activity on one computer. However, Defender for App Service looks at the bigger picture by analyzing data from multiple sources, including logs and the infrastructure hosting your applications. 

By combining this information, Defender for App Service can piece together the story of an attack, from its early signs circulating in the online world to actual compromises on customer machines. Even if Defender for App Service is deployed after an attack has already started, it's designed to detect ongoing attacks and help protect your web applications from further harm. 

In essence, Defender for App Service acts as a vigilant guard that not only keeps an eye on individual web applications but also looks out for broader patterns of attack across your entire Azure environment, helping to keep your applications safe and secure 

1. High Privilege Commands: Attackers may try to execute commands with elevated privileges to gain control over your system. Defender for Cloud can detect these attempts and alert you to take action. 
    
2. Cross-Platform Attacks: If you're running a Windows App Service but an attacker tries to execute Linux commands on it, Defender for Cloud can identify this unusual behavior and flag it as a potential threat. 
    
3. Fileless Attacks: Some attacks don't involve traditional malware files but instead rely on exploiting system vulnerabilities or using built-in tools for malicious activities. Defender for Cloud can detect these fileless attack behaviors and protect your system accordingly. 
    
4. Digital Currency Mining: Attackers may attempt to use your system's resources to mine cryptocurrencies without your consent. Defender for Cloud can detect the presence of digital currency mining tools and alert you to unauthorized usage. 
    
5. Other Malicious Code Execution Activities: Defender for Cloud is capable of identifying various other suspicious and malicious activities related to code execution, such as attempts to execute known malware or unauthorized scripts. 
    

Overall, Microsoft Defender for Cloud serves as a proactive defense mechanism, constantly monitoring your system for signs of malicious activity related to code execution 

A subdomain takeover can occur when you have a [DNS record](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/dns/dns-zones-records#dns-records) that points to a deprovisioned Azure resource. 

Dangling DNS entries 

Identification of Dangling DNS Entries: When you decommission a website on App Service and fail to remove its custom domain from the DNS registrar, Defender for App Service detects this and alerts you about the dangling DNS entry. 

Subdomain Takeover Risk: A dangling DNS entry creates an opportunity for threat actors to register the same domain or subdomain and set up a malicious website. When unsuspecting users visit the original domain, they are redirected to the threat actor's site, allowing them to carry out various malicious activities. 

Protection Mechanism: Defender for App Service helps mitigate this risk by notifying you to remove the dangling DNS entry, preventing potential subdomain takeovers and protecting your domain's reputation and users' security. 

Limitations 

Custom Domain Not Pointing to App Service: If your custom domain is not directly associated with an App Service resource, Defender for Cloud may not detect it as a dangling DNS entry. This means that if the domain is not actively pointing to an Azure App Service instance, the system may not recognize it as a potential security risk. 

Lack of Traffic Monitoring: Defender for Cloud relies on monitoring traffic to your website to identify custom domains associated with App Service resources. If there hasn't been any traffic to your website since the dangling DNS protection feature was enabled, there won't be any logs available to help identify the custom domain. As a result, Defender for Cloud may not trigger dangling DNS alerts in this scenario. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Risk associated with dangling DNS 

Loss of control over the content of the subdomain - Negative press about your organization's inability to secure its content, as well as the brand damage and loss of trust. 

Cookie harvesting from unsuspecting visitors - It's common for web apps to expose session cookies to subdomains (*.contoso.com), consequently any subdomain can access them. Threat actors can use subdomain takeover to build an authentic looking page, trick unsuspecting users to visit it, and harvest their cookies (even secure cookies). A common misconception is that using SSL certificates protects your site, and your users' cookies, from a takeover. However, a threat actor can use the hijacked subdomain to apply for and receive a valid SSL certificate. Valid SSL certificates grant them access to secure cookies and can further increase the perceived legitimacy of the malicious site. 

Phishing campaigns - Authentic-looking subdomains might be used in phishing campaigns. This is true for malicious sites and for MX records that would allow the threat actor to receive emails addressed to a legitimate subdomain of a known-safe brand. 

Further risks - Malicious sites might be used to escalate into other classic attacks such as XSS, CSRF, CORS bypass, and more. 

Cookie Harvesting: Many websites use session cookies to track user activity and maintain their logged-in status. These cookies are often shared across subdomains (e.g., *.contoso.com), meaning any subdomain can access them. Threat actors can take over a subdomain and create a fake webpage that looks legitimate. They trick unsuspecting users into visiting this fake page, where their session cookies are harvested, even if they're supposed to be secure. Even if the original website uses SSL certificates to encrypt data, threat actors can obtain valid SSL certificates for hijacked subdomains, giving them access to secure cookies and making their malicious sites appear legitimate. 

Phishing Campaigns: Threat actors can also use authentic-looking subdomains in phishing campaigns. They create fake websites that mimic legitimate ones, often using subdomains that closely resemble trusted brands. Users are lured into entering sensitive information, such as login credentials or personal details, thinking they're on a legitimate site. Additionally, threat actors can set up MX (Mail Exchange) records to receive emails addressed to a legitimate subdomain of a well-known brand. This allows them to intercept and potentially exploit emails intended for the legitimate domain, further enhancing the effectiveness of their phishing campaigns. 

Defender for Key Vault 

Attacks that may happen on key vault 

Unauthorized Access: Attackers may attempt to gain unauthorized access to the keys, secrets, or certificates stored in Key Vault. This could involve brute-force attacks, credential stuffing, or exploiting vulnerabilities in access controls. 

Data Leakage: Attackers may attempt to extract sensitive information from Key Vault through various means, such as exploiting misconfigurations, insecure APIs, or vulnerabilities in the Key Vault service itself. 

Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) Attacks: Attackers may attempt to intercept and manipulate communication between applications and Key Vault, potentially gaining access to sensitive data or performing unauthorized operations 

Microsoft Defender for Key Vault detects unusual and potentially harmful attempts to access or exploit Key Vault accounts. 

It can detect unauthorized access attempts, unusual access patterns, or potential data leakage incidents. 

Some examples of these alerts include “Access from a suspicious IP address to a Key Vault” and “Unusual user accessed a Key Vault 

 Key vault firewall disabled 

when you create a new key vault, the Azure Key Vault firewall is disabled. All applications and Azure services can access the key vault and send requests to the key vault. This configuration doesn't mean that any user will be able to perform operations on your key vault. The key vault still restricts access to secrets, keys, and certificates stored in key vault by requiring Microsoft Entra authentication and access policy permission 

Enabled 

When you enable the Key Vault Firewall, you'll be given an option to 'Allow Trusted Microsoft Services to bypass this firewall.' The trusted services list does not cover every single Azure service. For example, Azure DevOps isn't on the trusted services list. This does not imply that services that do not appear on the trusted services list are not trusted or are insecure 

If you would like to authorize a particular service to access key vault through the Key Vault Firewall, you can add its IP Address to the key vault firewall allowlist 

There is a limit of 1000 CIDR ranges for this case.
